The architects saw one - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini kindergarten here, with everything that belongs to it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to the employees of Arch.Design since last year.
From the first designs for the new Avriopoint building, the design and architecture firm Arch.Design, from whose studios a whole series of well-known Brno buildings come from, counted on the premises for its company mini-kindergarten.
In wise foresight, because most of his 90 employees are in the Babyboom age and the company is anxious that the project participants return to their workplace as soon as possible.
Together with the opportunity to work in a shorter way, kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer to its employees in the concept of their social program.
This makes it easier for the civil engineers to reconcile their demanding profession and child care.
The Minikindergarten is an original idea of the employees of Arch.Design and with the support of the management, they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The mini-kindergarten is financed by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operational Programme from the European Social Fund and the Czech Republic State Budget.
Thanks to this financing (subsidies of CZK 2, 8 million) the necessary facilities and equipment could be procured and for the duration of 2 years qualified personnel and operation is provided.
After 2 years of funding, the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue running the mini kindergarten for 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took an entire year, with the company Economy Rating providing active assistance in the application processing.
The children are taken care of by full-time qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can visit children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is about a mini kindergarten, only 5 children may be present at the same time, but the day will alternate over several children.
The kindergarten business is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in relation to the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is individual education and care, the programme content in the mini kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the supporting programme of pre-school education.
The children not only play here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to pre-school lessons, while also learning English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer available to children.
What more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time and thus eliminate the stress when they pick up the children from a far-off kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also emerging here.
Arch.Design thus joined the Czech companies, which offer significant benefits when recruiting new employees, which are family-friendly and strengthen their personnel marketing through such programs.
A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof mutates like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló by Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
Of the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms was nicknamed "Knobenhaus".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile chips and mosaics, the shed-like facades and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The facade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and living beings.
It is only when you look more closely that you notice that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the whole façade appears even more plastic, dramatic and the special illumination enhances the shine of the colours.
The same sweeping lines and entwined forms also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even peepholes and groins.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was built by the reconstruction of a house dating from 1877, carried out by architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but in the end he agreed with Gaudí's idea of an unusual and also cheaper reconstruction.
However, Antoni Gaudí did not design the Casa Batlló apartment building alone.
He worked with architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was precisely on its drawing board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner and the use of mosaics on the façade were his idea.
However, numerous other sculptors and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá house in Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was nicknamed "Knobenhaus" by the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others, on the other hand, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "cheating house".
It is also said that the sword of Saint George, the patron of Catalonia, is depicted at the top of the building.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed for the house a central heating system that was unique at the time, with ventilation channels and typical fireplaces.
Somewhat bizarre, her 45-degree inclination is already on.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be deceived by them.
Before construction began, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later the city fathers were so horrified at the completion that they demanded remedy.
Among other things, the councillors also came up against the fact that the construction with its pillars even interfered with the public sidewalk.
However, changes were no longer made, on the contrary - only fifteen days after the district's request for a permit to rent the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The homeowner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor was a social salon, on the third floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the remodeling removed all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger society could chat comfortably, without having to renounce a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
The house received by Gaudí's reconstruction besides a new facade also a rather unusual roof and two more floors.
Gaudí's play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is disguised and the courtyards is impressive.
The play of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
In doing so, he simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colours, which, on the contrary, absorb sunlight.
The house Casa Batlló, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can be visited by everyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is open to the public.
The homeowners decided not to take this step until the year, on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was discovered that this is a fairly profitable business, the visits were kept, even they were extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
The price for visiting the monument is not a cardboard handle, however, it amounts to 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the house dwellers and visit him at home.
