Zapatero and the red line of Germany
Berlin has chosen to retain the euro, but at the same time has established conditions for the whole of the European Union.
The tensions in the markets have triggered a double response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has presented new adjustment measures, starting with tax reductions for small and micro-enterprises, regulation of temporary employment companies or the lifting of the 426 euro support for unemployed people who do not receive unemployment benefits, up to the privatisation of 49 percent of AENA, the administration of Barajas and El Prat airports, and 30 percent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, with the help of former Prime Minister Felipe González, the Deputy Head of Government, Elena Salgado, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as the person responsible for evoking the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It is anticipated that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her public relations work.
On the contrary, this is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany takes a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which clashes with the maintenance of the traditional traditions of a large part of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second is the reintroduction of the German Mark - although it sounds more like science fiction at the moment - supported by a large part of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third is a restructuring of the euro according to German proposals. This means: more macro-economic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of the countries that exceed the requirements; possible suspension of payments by some countries and the extension of the costs of potential adaptation measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been evident for some time. That is why there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government withdrew a constitutional reform to prevent this from 2016 onwards.
This was the first sign of the drift between what Germany deemed necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was set by the Central European country when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to save Greece.
But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public opinion and the public opinion were absolutely against saving Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October Merkel comes out again with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union's agreements in order to enable a country to be saved and at the same time oblige private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it precipitated the Ireland crisis and all the following.
But their proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been adopted, and in the coming months we will be participating in the reform of the European Union, which will allow these measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that - even if unpopular measures must be taken now - the old functioning of the euro will no longer exist from this date onwards.
2013 will be the year of birth of a new currency area in which the conflicting countries will be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent and in this case the private sector will have to bear part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we have to take a hard course in growth, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as led by Spain in booming times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly not understand.
It is not just a matter of bringing the government deficit down to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much tougher.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is to cheat ourselves.
I hope that the current turmoil will move into more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this, too, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the large companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures yesterday) points out that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in his own house has prepared its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it does not look like something would change.
Among the opportunities envisaged, the fact that we would have to leave the euro area, which is full of little serious countries, cannot be ruled out.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sport and regularity
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The exclusion, allegedly instigated by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against the Ajax in the Champions League, resulted in a lot of ink being shed on whether or not it was an unsporting act and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls for the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since the Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will meet the prescribed penalty in the next league match against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game phase without cards.
Finally, UEFA's Disciplinary Committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules followed in this sport.
Part of the ensuing debate about the case is due to the fact that a team from the Real Madrid football club (who in his anthem pretended nobleness and honor and on other occasions punished his players for similar incidents) played the lead role in this, and to the dramatization by Mourinho, who added one episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this practice, which is not expressly prohibited by the Statutes, contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether these acts constitute a rule-by-rule. Indeed, this approach adheres to the Statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this matter, the damage caused to the sport spirit should be investigated.
The sport spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid that the opposing players draw an unjustified benefit from the opposing team. This did not happen either.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally mean by false play or rule avoidance, because the circumvention of the rule was not carried out secretly in order to avoid a sanction, but it should be as conspicuous as possible for it to be punished by the referee.
The players waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders drew from the deliberate fouls.
It should be pointed out here that the rival was not put in a more unfavourable position nor was there any advantage for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that his own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next game phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, to a certain degree uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually also withdraw. Moreover, with this approach, the players receive a sanction and pass into the second card cycle, in which they exit with a card less than in the first cycle due to card accumulation.
This does not make it clear whether it really is an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not directed against the sport spirit, which also includes strategic decisions, in order to benefit from the rules as much as possible.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent a sanction (this would actually be a clear case of rule avoidance), they rather wanted to choose when they would submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding or fleeing a punishment.
Although the boundary between inventiveness and the control environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that polemics arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the kind of rule transmission provoked.
The damage done by these actions to the principles of sport is less ethical than aesthetic.
