The US changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Persons must present themselves to the visa application service offices before they talk to the consulate, thereby reducing the costs of waiting times.
As of January 10, 2011, procedures for applying for a visa at the United States Embassy and consulates will change.
In the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves to the visa application services (ASC, the initial letters in English) before they speak at the consulate.
The staff of the ASC shall record the biometric data of the applicant, which shall be verified by the consulate before the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of the visa is falling, as it is no longer necessary to pay separately the appointment, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed over.
The applicant shall make only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the $140 counter for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for handers and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not need to have a conversation at the consulate, they only have to imagine the nearest ASC, where they present their documents and their fingerprints are taken.
Since the biometric data are collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the conversation at the consulate remain there less time than before.
Those who apply for the visa at the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo no longer have to pay the service surcharge of 26 dollars.
Additional information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassisy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
