Global plan for the renewal of lighting
Yesterday in Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas emissions (CFCs), equivalent to almost a third of the additional reduction that needs to be achieved in order to stabilise the Earth's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete large-scale projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments from developed countries.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem would be avoided in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFC delivered to the earth due to lighting if the white-burning pears, which are still a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or better still, light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases of the worldwide fleet.
Last year, in Copenhagen, major emissions emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt would have to be deducted from this balance sheet in order to stabilise the increase in climate by 2 degrees Celsius from today to 2020 in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white annealing pears 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs the energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED incandescent bulbs this energy requirement is reduced again by two times.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last between 6000 and 10,000 hours on average.
The new LED incandescent bulbs, such as those put on the market this week by the manufacturer Philips - this company, incidentally, participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-hot bulb, which gives a hint of the savings of the replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that this completely new light bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a control resistance.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent pears have reserves because they contain mercury and therefore they have to be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless the producers provide a reception centre.
According to the report, however, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit much more mercury to produce the electricity wasted by the white-burning pears.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would make thanks to this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save one billion dollars a year on the purchase of electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which means an equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants whose construction would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
